olitical representation that gave rise to anticolonial nationalism. This conceptualization of the “post-mandarin” promises to have a significant impact on the fields of literary theory, postcolonial studies, East Asian and Southeast Asian studies, and modernist studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGender identity in literature. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aVietnamese literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in literature. 4aAsian Studies. 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aColonial Intellectuals.  aColonial Modernity.  aFrench Colonialism.  aModernism.  aModernist Literature.  aRealism.  aVietnamese Culture.  agender.  amasculinity.  apostcolonial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823273164zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823273164423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823273164/original  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK